msgid "Qualify the `use`."
msgstr ""

#: src/2166-impl-only-use.md:62
msgid ""
"The problem is that if we qualify the `use`, what name do we give the trait? "
"We’re not even referring to it directly."
msgstr ""

#: src/2166-impl-only-use.md:69
msgid ""
"This will work but seems a bit like a hack because rustc forces us to give a "
"name to something we won’t use in our types."
msgstr ""

#: src/2166-impl-only-use.md:72
msgid ""
"This RFC suggests to solve this by adding the possibility to explicitly "
"state that we won’t directly refer to that trait, but we want the impls:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2166-impl-only-use.md:79
msgid "Guide-level explanation"
msgstr ""

#: src/2166-impl-only-use.md:82
msgid ""
"Qualifying a `use` with `_` on a trait imports the trait’s `impl`s but not "
"the symbol directly. It’s handy if you don’t use the trait’s symbol in your "
"type and if you redefine the symbol to something else."
msgstr ""

#: src/2166-impl-only-use.md:86
msgid ""
"The `_` means that you “don’t care about the name rustc will use for that "
"qualified `use`“."
msgstr ""

#: src/2166-impl-only-use.md:88
msgid "Reference-level explanation"
msgstr ""

#: src/2166-impl-only-use.md:91
msgid ""
"`use Trait as _` needs to desugar into `use Trait as SomeGenSym`. With this "
"scheme, global imports and exports can work properly with such items, i.e. "
"import / re-export them."
msgstr ""

